post_text:
Happy Friday Illini!!
One day left and we are already one week down.
Kids, welcome back. We missed you more than you will ever know.
New students welcome. We can‚Äôt wait till we can greet you in person.
Staff, you are amazing. The amount of time you are putting toward this year is incredible. Your positive attitudes are inspiring.
Parents, you are rock stars. It is a two cups of coffee morning for you. No wait, you get the whole pot and a donut. You are asking the right questions, setting the right tone, just the right amount of confused still, and determined to figure it all out.
I am right there with you all. I am a kid at heart who loved seeing everyone the first few days. I am new to the remote learning world and still mildly confused. I am part of that staff, and I have a little one who I am trying to assist. That being said, I will pour myself that second cup of coffee and toast to a great first Friday.
Keep soarin‚Äô Eagles. Stay strong and know one day we will back together in the classrooms. Until then, get that computer charged. See you in a little bit.
Carla Lasley

post_text:
Today‚Äôs news was, well, devastating. We were so close and our hearts are broken. Staff left today so ready and excited for Monday. Our students, families, and communities safety is priority number one, but do not doubt our thoughts immediately turn to you and the short notice this gives you. We had no choice but to take this course of action. That being said we are going to take this weekend to reset. We will be hard at work next week trying to make sure that we can get everything together so we are all ready to begin on the 17th. Please take a moment to assure our kids that we are still going to have a great year. We are going to learn incredible things and keep ourselves ready to resume in person as soon as we can. Hang in there Illini. We will get through this stronger than ever.
Carla Lasley, Principal

Good Morning Illini!!!
Have I told you lately that you are amazing? Kindergarten and 1st grade in person supply drop off/remote books and supply pick up, BIG SUCCESS! Whether your family opted for in person or remote learning, one thing is very clear, you are ready to get this school year underway! Thank you for your patience, kind words, questions, and willingness to take this unprecedented journey with us step by step. We are a team. United we stand!
Today is 2nd grade in person supply drop off and remote learner book pick up from 5-7 pm. Just pull up and we will come to your vehicle. No need to get out, we will take your supplies from your vehicle, or bring your supplies to your vehicle.
We are so happy to see you, talk with you, coordinate with you, and your support means the world.
See you tonight second grade parents!!
#IlliniStrong

Registration & Remote Update

Please make sure you get on-line at Teacher Ease and register for school no later than July 27. We need to get classes created for all learning options.

This afternoon, the IL State Board released 103 pages of new guidance for reopening schools. There will be updates to our plans coming. One change which many of you asked about, is that the requirement for the Dr. note to go remote has been removed.

I will get updates to our plans out soon. Thank you for all of your patience as the guidance, rules, numbers, and phases all change daily during this pandemic.

Sincerely,

M. Stines

At this time, some Doctor's offices are not seeing patients for physicals and immunizations. I wanted to share that Kevin Ponciroli, a Pediatrician with A to Z Pediatrics, is offering assistance to kids by allowing them to come in for a one-time physical without changing their primary care location. All insurance is accepted including Medicaid plans. To be seen, they require an up to date shot record to be brought in.
Here is the contact information.
Kevin Ponciroli, MD
Atozpediatrics.com
Office Phone: 618-345-5437

Day 18 of weekday remote learning Illini. Parents you are crushing it, coping with it, navigating it, readjusting it, and at times fed up with it. Take a moment today to be proud of yourself. Take a moment to see how proud you are of your children, who also have had to ebb, flow, adjust, and flex. Many of you are still working as an Essential Workers and we want to Thank You. All of you have a new job title of educator you can attach to your thousand other titles you have to wear in a day. We hear you Illini, and we appreciate you. We are in this together and we are here for you. Keeping our kids and community safe has to stay our number one priority.
Stay Home
Stay Healthy
Stay Strong
#UnitedCommunity
Mrs. Lasley

post_text:
Illini Parents:
For some of you at this point it is like the end of winter break. The time together was nice, but let‚Äôs face it, it can be exhausting. The honeymoon is over and some of you might be struggling a bit. Remember we are here. Need a call from the principal to discuss a lack of wanting to attempt to try the work? Need a video chat with me or Ms Davis to talk about concerns you or your students are having? Maybe your student has a birthday and you‚Äôd like us to call or come by and sing Happy Birthday to your child in the driveway(a good 6 ft away promise). Maybe your child has been doing really great or worked hard on a difficult task and you would like a certificate of recognition sent from us in the mail.
Just know we are here to support you. We know your job as a parent was hard enough before this pandemic, and we understand the need for support now. I am just an email away. Feel free to reach out.
Sincerely,
Mrs. Lasley

shared_text:
Fairview Heights Police
March 28 at 2:47 PM ¬∑

Many departments across the metro-east area are receiving more and more complaints of teens and young adults playing basketball, soccer, and participating in other outdoor gatherings, basically disregarding social distancing.

The past few weeks have been mentally exhausting for everyone of all ages. If we continue to follow the recommendations from the medical community, we know that we can lessen the spread of COVID-19. Please remember that everyone has an obligation to live responsibly and shelter in place.

It is critical for all of us to be thoughtful of our vulnerable groups, the elderly, and those with pre-existing health conditions. COVID-19 can cause death or severe sickness if contracted. Be a part of the solution and be mindful of others. We will get through this!

post_text: Buses will be out tomorrow between 10:20-11:45 am delivering lunches again. They are running the kids normal bus route and you will need to be at their normal bus stop. Lastly, thank you to all the volunteers who are dividing out, loading, and delivering each day. You are so appreciated.

post_text:
Good Evening Everyone,

This afternoon Gov. Pritzker issued an executive order for all Illinois Schools to be closed due to the COVID-19 virus outbreak. We will be closed from Monday, March 16-Monday, March 30. We would like for our kiddos to still have learning opportunities available to them. We have a wide variety of on-line resources, google platforms, and some may prepare hard copies. The staff will be working to get materials together for students to work on during this time. You and your child will be able to pick up any materials they may need on Monday from 3:00-7:00pm.

We are also working to coordinate a meal program for our students during this time. Additional information regarding this will be released early next week.

Respectfully,

Matt Stines
